## 2. Medical and Health Insurance Claims Data Experience / 医疗与健康保险理赔数据经验

**English**

I have approximately three years of experience working with medical and pharmacy claims data in real-world evidence, healthcare analytics, and health outcomes research. My work has involved longitudinal insurance records containing diagnosis codes, procedure codes, prescription claims, inpatient and outpatient services, emergency department visits, provider information, enrollment history, place of service, and healthcare cost variables.

I use claims data to identify eligible patients, construct study cohorts, determine index dates, define baseline and follow-up periods, and derive treatment exposures, comorbidities, outcomes, and healthcare utilization measures. For example, I may identify patients with a disease using diagnosis codes, require continuous health plan enrollment during a baseline period, identify a treatment initiation date, and follow patients for hospitalization, treatment switching, discontinuation, or other outcomes.

My claims analyses have included treatment initiation, switching, discontinuation, adherence, persistence, hospitalization, emergency department use, outpatient visits, specialist services, medication use, and disease-related healthcare utilization. I have also supported economic analyses involving total medical costs, pharmacy costs, inpatient costs, outpatient costs, emergency department costs, and disease-specific costs.

When analyzing cost data, I distinguish among billed charges, allowed amounts, insurer-paid amounts, patient-paid amounts, and total paid amounts. These variables do not represent the same economic concept, so their definitions must be aligned with the study objective.

A major part of claims research is establishing continuous enrollment. Continuous insurance coverage helps ensure that the absence of a claim is more reasonably interpreted as the absence of an observed healthcare event rather than loss of data availability. I therefore assess medical and pharmacy benefit eligibility, enrollment gaps, plan changes, and the completeness of the observable baseline and follow-up periods.

I also evaluate data quality issues such as duplicate claims, adjusted claims, rejected or reversed pharmacy claims, missing provider information, inconsistent dates, and incomplete cost fields. Pharmacy claims often contain reversals or resubmissions, so I apply appropriate logic to avoid counting a prescription that was not ultimately dispensed.

Claims data are valuable because they provide broad population coverage, longitudinal healthcare utilization, and relatively complete reimbursed medical activity. However, they are primarily generated for billing and reimbursement rather than research. Diagnosis codes may reflect rule-out diagnoses, coding practices, or reimbursement incentives. Medication claims indicate dispensing, but not necessarily actual ingestion. Clinical details such as disease severity, performance status, tumor stage, laboratory results, imaging findings, and physician reasoning may be missing.

For this reason, I assess whether claims data are fit for the specific research question and clearly document their limitations. Where possible, I use validated code-based algorithms, require repeated diagnoses, incorporate procedure or medication evidence, link claims with EHR or registry data, and perform sensitivity analyses using alternative definitions.

