I use EHR data to identify study populations, establish index dates, define baseline and follow-up periods, and derive exposures, outcomes, comorbidities, disease characteristics, and healthcare utilization measures. Compared with claims data, EHR data generally provide greater clinical detail, including laboratory values, vital signs, disease severity, symptoms, and information documented in clinical notes.

My work includes translating clinical research questions into reproducible EHR cohort definitions. This may involve defining inclusion and exclusion criteria, creating diagnosis and procedure code lists, identifying medication orders or administrations, applying laboratory thresholds, and defining outcomes using combinations of structured variables and clinical documentation.

For example, a treatment exposure may be identified from medication orders, administration records, infusion records, or pharmacy data. Each source has a different interpretation. A medication order indicates prescribing intent, while an administration record provides stronger evidence that treatment was actually delivered. Therefore, the appropriate exposure definition depends on the research question and the data source.

I have also worked with longitudinal patient records to evaluate treatment pathways, disease progression, clinical outcomes, and patterns of healthcare utilization. When patients have repeated laboratory measurements or encounters, I define clinically appropriate observation windows and rules for selecting baseline, follow-up, maximum, minimum, or nearest measurements.

At McGill University, I supported projects involving EHR and clinical data related to COVID-19, maternal health, and emergency care. My responsibilities included data cleaning, cohort identification, variable derivation, and patient-level analysis. I also gained experience using natural language processing approaches to extract meaningful information from clinical text when structured data were incomplete.

In multi-source RWE projects, I have worked with datasets linking EHR information to claims, registry, laboratory, or mortality data. Linking these sources can combine the clinical detail of EHRs with the broader longitudinal utilization captured by claims.

I routinely evaluate EHR fitness for purpose. Key issues include missing data, variation in documentation practices, duplicate records, changes in EHR systems, inconsistent coding, care received outside the contributing network, and differences in laboratory units or reference ranges.

Missing EHR values are often informative. A laboratory test may be missing because the physician did not consider it clinically necessary, because the patient received the test outside the network, or because the result was not integrated into the system. Therefore, missingness cannot automatically be assumed to be random.

Medication orders may not confirm that a patient filled or took the medication. Diagnoses may be entered for billing, problem-list maintenance, or clinical suspicion. Some outcomes may be incompletely documented. I address these limitations through validation, alternative definitions, linkage, sensitivity analyses, and transparent reporting.

From a programming perspective, I have created reproducible EHR processing workflows using SAS, SQL, R, and Python. I validate cohort counts, temporal relationships, variable distributions, missingness patterns, and consistency with the study protocol.

