## 7. Integrating Oncology SDTM and ADaM Experience with RWE / 将肿瘤学 SDTM/ADaM 经验与 RWE 相结合

**English**

My oncology SDTM and ADaM experience is directly relevant to RWE because the underlying concepts of population definition, endpoint derivation, temporal alignment, censoring, and traceability apply to both settings.

In clinical trials, the protocol defines eligibility, treatment assignment, visit schedules, response criteria, and outcome assessment procedures. In RWE studies, those elements must be operationalized from routinely collected data.

For example, overall survival may be relatively straightforward if reliable death data are available. Progression-free survival is more difficult because progression assessments may not occur at standardized intervals in routine care. A real-world progression endpoint may therefore require abstraction from radiology reports, oncology notes, tumor measurements, treatment changes, or registry data.

Clinical trial experience also helps distinguish between highly controlled endpoint definitions and real-world proxies. The analyst should not assume that a claims code or treatment change is equivalent to protocol-defined progression without validation.

My CDISC experience supports structured variable definitions, metadata, traceability, and quality control. My RWE experience adds knowledge of confounding, selection bias, missingness, data fragmentation, and measurement error.

Together, these skills allow me to design RWE analyses that are clinically meaningful and methodologically transparent.

