## 24. Linear Regression Experience / 线性回归经验

**English**

I have experience using linear regression in clinical trial and RWE analyses to evaluate relationships between continuous outcomes and demographic, clinical, treatment-related, or healthcare factors.

Examples of continuous outcomes include: laboratory values, change from baseline, healthcare costs, length of stay, quality-of-life scores, blood pressure, biomarker levels, and treatment duration.

I use simple linear regression for one predictor and multiple linear regression when adjusting for several covariates.

I report regression coefficients, confidence intervals, and p-values. The coefficient represents the expected change in the outcome associated with a one-unit change in the predictor, holding other variables constant.

I assess: linearity, independence, normality of residuals, homoscedasticity, multicollinearity, outliers, leverage, and influential observations.

I review residual plots and diagnostic measures. If assumptions are not met, I consider variable transformation, robust standard errors, generalized linear models, quantile regression, or other alternatives.

Cost data are often right-skewed and may not be well modeled using ordinary linear regression without modification. Depending on the objective, I may use log transformation or a generalized linear model with a suitable distribution and link function.

In observational research, linear regression can adjust for measured covariates, but it does not automatically remove bias from unmeasured confounding or model misspecification.

