## 25. Logistic Regression Experience / 逻辑回归经验

**English**

I have experience using logistic regression to analyze binary outcomes in clinical trials and RWE studies.

Examples include: treatment response versus no response, hospitalization versus no hospitalization, adverse event versus no adverse event, disease progression versus no progression, treatment discontinuation versus continuation, and readmission versus no readmission.

I use univariable logistic regression to examine individual associations and multivariable logistic regression to adjust for demographic, clinical, and treatment-related covariates.

I report odds ratios and 95% confidence intervals. I interpret odds ratios carefully, particularly when outcomes are common, because the odds ratio may differ substantially from the risk ratio.

I assess: correct outcome coding, linearity in the logit for continuous predictors, multicollinearity, sparse cells, separation, influential observations, model calibration, model discrimination, and interaction terms.

For rare events or separation, I may consider exact logistic regression, penalized methods, or Firth logistic regression.

In RWE studies, I also use logistic regression to estimate propensity scores. The predicted probability of treatment can then be used for matching, stratification, weighting, or covariate adjustment.

I select propensity-score variables based primarily on subject-matter knowledge and their relationship with treatment assignment and outcome, rather than relying only on automated statistical selection.

