## 26. Survival Analysis Experience / 生存分析经验

**English**

I have extensive experience conducting survival analyses in oncology clinical trials and real-world evidence studies.

My experience includes: Kaplan–Meier estimation, log-rank tests, Cox proportional hazards models, median survival, landmark survival rates, hazard ratios, confidence intervals, censoring rules, competing risks, and time-dependent variables.

Clinical trial endpoints I have supported include overall survival, progression-free survival, duration of response, event-free survival, time to progression, and time to treatment failure.

RWE endpoints may include overall survival, hospitalization-free survival, time to treatment discontinuation, time to next treatment, readmission, disease progression, or time to adverse events.

I carefully define: time zero, event definition, event date, censoring date, follow-up period, analysis population, data cutoff, treatment switching, and loss to follow-up.

Kaplan–Meier methods estimate the survival function while accounting for right censoring. I report median survival and confidence intervals when estimable, as well as survival probabilities at clinically relevant time points.

The log-rank test compares survival curves but does not adjust for covariates.

The Cox proportional hazards model estimates hazard ratios while adjusting for covariates. I assess the proportional hazards assumption using graphical methods, Schoenfeld residuals, time interactions, or other diagnostics.

If proportional hazards do not hold, I may consider stratified Cox models, time-varying coefficients, restricted mean survival time, milestone survival, or other methods.

In RWE studies, censoring may be informative. For example, patients may disappear from a database because they changed insurers, moved to another health system, or lost eligibility. I assess the censoring mechanism and may use sensitivity analyses or inverse probability of censoring weights.

