## 28. Missing Data / 缺失数据

**English**

My approach to missing data begins with understanding why the data are missing and how missingness relates to the exposure, outcome, and patient characteristics.

I assess: the percentage missing, missingness by treatment group, missingness over time, missingness by site or provider, associations between missingness and observed variables, and whether missingness may be informative.

Common approaches include: complete-case analysis, missing-indicator methods, single imputation, multiple imputation, inverse probability weighting, model-based methods, and sensitivity analyses.

Complete-case analysis may be reasonable when missingness is limited and unlikely to produce material bias, but it can reduce precision and introduce selection bias.

Multiple imputation can be appropriate when missingness can be reasonably modeled using observed information. The imputation model should include variables related to missingness, exposure, outcome, and analysis variables.

In EHR data, missingness often reflects clinical decision-making. A laboratory test may be absent because it was not ordered. This makes missingness potentially informative and requires careful interpretation.

I report the extent of missing data, the method used, assumptions, and sensitivity analyses.

